{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fb5f34e7-df52-4710-a1e0-8e3d7f1ffcd3","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws` (xUnit/NUnit) instead. This is more precise and doesn't pass if the wrong line throws:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why?**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws the expected exception, masking bugs\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call\n- You can also capture and inspect the exception:\n\n```csharp\nvar ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n    () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\nAssert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"989729c7-e21f-4b48-989a-dc117525600e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to modernize a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a straightforward knowledge question - no tools needed.","outputTokens":275,"requestId":"4C4B:2BC959:B7E3E3:E58F28:6A0130BF"},"id":"a43e05d9-6cc4-46fd-9039-2b0dde14e105","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:28:38.082Z","parentId":"924d38c8-e7d6-47ca-b779-4c6dad66c9cd"}
